Assessment Object Objective¶

  • Train a model to predict defaulting behavior.
  • Choose scoring function(s)
  • Evaluate your model and discuss the results.

The notebooks is sectioned into 5 parts with comments

  • Data Cleaning and preprocessing
    Goal: To check for missing and duplicated records
  • Features Engineering
    Goal: derive new features than can be used for risk decisioning
  • EDA
    Goal: To understand the characteristics of good and bad credit using the independent variables
  • Compute WOE AND IV
    Goal: to assess the predictive power and strength of association between categorical variables and the target variable in credit risk modeling Goal:
  • Modeling and Evalutaion
    Goal: Selecting an appropriate machine learning algorithm to predict defaulting behavior.

In [17]:
def risk_flag(dataframe):
    doc = { 0: 'Good',
            1: 'Bad'}
    
    dataframe['risk_flag'] = dataframe['default'].replace(doc)
    return dataframe

Basic descriptive stats¶

  • The "checking_balance" has a wide range of values, with some negative values and a maximum of 999, indicating possible outliers.
  • The "months_loan_duration" ranges from 4 to 72 months, with a median of 18 months.
  • The "amount" of loans varies significantly, ranging from 250 to 18424, with a median of 2319.5.
  • The "savings_balance" column has missing values (count: 817) and shows variability from 0 to 19972.
  • The "installment_rate" is categorical, with four distinct values (1, 2, 3, 4).
  • The "age" of customers ranges from 19 to 75, with a mean of approximately 35.5 years.
  • The "dependents" column has mostly one value (1), with a small number of records having two dependents (max: 2).

Observations

  • In the 'checking_balance' column, we encountered cases where customers had negative balances. Consequently, we engineered a new feature called 'checking balance flag' i.e for customers with positive bal are named(positive balance), negative values as negative balance, and customers with no balance as (no balance)

  • For the 'savings_balance' column, we introduced a flag to indicate whether a customer has a savings balance or not.

  • Regarding the 'employment_length' column, which originally captured durations in months or years, we created a new column to standardize employment length by converting it to months.

  • Similar to 'employment_length', we derived a new column for 'residence_history' to handle the duration of residence in months.

  • For the 'Telephone' column, we generated a flag to distinguish customers with phone numbers from those without (missing values).

In [25]:
def create_balance_flag(df, column_name):
    """This function takes a DataFrame (df) as 
    input and creates a new column called 'checking_balance_flag'. 
    It then sets the flag based on the specified conditions"""
    # Create a new column for the flag with default value 'positive_balance'
    flag_column = f'{column_name}_flag'
    df[flag_column] = f'pos_{column_name}'
    
    # Update the flag based on conditions
    df.loc[df[column_name] < 0, flag_column] = f'neg_{column_name}'
    df.loc[df[column_name].isnull(), flag_column] = f'no_{column_name}'
    
    return df
data=create_balance_flag(data,'checking_balance')
In [26]:
def create_savings_balance_flag(df):
    # Create a new column for the flag with default value 'no_saving_bal'
    df['savings_balance_flag'] = 'no_saving_bal'
    
    # Update the flag to 'has_saving_bal' for non-null savings balance values
    df.loc[df['savings_balance'].notnull(), 'savings_balance_flag'] = 'has_saving_bal'
    
    return df
data=create_savings_balance_flag(data)

In [28]:
def convert_to_months(df, column_name):
    new_column_name = f'{column_name}_month'

    # Extract the numeric portion of the strings in the column
    df[new_column_name] = df[column_name].str.extract('(\d+)').astype(float)

    # Multiply the values by 12 if the strings contain 'year' to convert to months
    df.loc[df[column_name].str.contains('year', case=False), new_column_name] *= 12

    return df
data=convert_to_months(data,'employment_length')
data=convert_to_months(data,'residence_history')

def create_telephone_flag(df):
    # Create a new column for the flag with default value 'no_telephone'
    df['telephone_flag'] = 'no_telephone'
    
    # Update the flag to 'telephone' for non-null telephone values
    df.loc[df['telephone'].notnull(), 'telephone_flag'] = 'has_telephone'
    
    return df
data=create_telephone_flag(data)

def convert_to_string_and_fill_missing(df):
    # Convert all columns to string (object)
    df = df.astype(str)
    
    # Fill missing values with "missing"
    df = df.replace('nan', 'missing', regex=True)
    
    return df

I'm using the category_encoders , compared to the dummy variable encoding. Reason is because they make data smaller, work faster, and handle new categories well. They also encode ordered data and use target information, avoiding issues like overfitting and are easily fitted into data processing pipelines.

https://gsarantitis.wordpress.com/2019/07/16/how-to-persist-categorical-encoding-in-machine-learning-deployment-phase/

X = data_m.drop('risk_flag', axis=1)

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state= 42)

I selected the Logistic regression and random forest for the choice of my algorithm

Reason

  • Logistic regression provides interpretability of coefficients, enabling understanding of feature impact on the target, making it suitable for regulatory compliance and risk assessment.
  • Random forest captures complex relationships between features and the target, handles outliers well, and offers feature importance analysis, making it suitable for accurate prediction and risk assessment in credit scoring.

Features with larger absolute coefficients have a stronger impact on the target variable i.e

  • checking_balance_flag
  • foreign_worker

Observations:

The model shows better performance in predicting the "Good" class compared to the "Bad" class, as indicated by higher precision, recall, and F1-score for the "Good" class.

The recall for the "Bad" class is relatively low (32%), which suggests that the model struggles to correctly identify instances of the "Bad" class.

The model has high precision (76%) for the "Good" class, indicating that it is good at correctly predicting "Good" instances among the total positive predictions.

The overall accuracy of the model is 74%, suggesting that it classifies 74% of instances correctly.

The macro-averaged F1-score (63%) considers the balance between the two classes, providing an overall assessment of the model's performance.

The weighted-averaged F1-score (71%) accounts for class imbalances in the dataset, giving higher weight to the larger class (in this case, the "Good" class).

Observations for Random Forest results:

  • The Random Forest model has a slightly higher accuracy (75%) compared to Logistic Regression (74%).
  • Precision for the "Bad" class is 64%, while recall is 41%, indicating the model's ability to correctly identify true "Bad" instances but with a relatively high false positive rate.
  • For the "Good" class, precision is 78%, and recall is 90%, indicating a good balance of precision and recall for the "Good" predictions.
  • The F1-score for the "Bad" class is 50%, while for the "Good" class, it is 83%, indicating better overall performance in predicting the "Good" class.
  • The macro-averaged F1-score for Random Forest is 67%, which is slightly higher than Logistic Regression's macro-averaged F1-score (63%).
  • The weighted-averaged F1-score for Random Forest is 73%, showing a good balance of F1-scores for both classes, similar to Logistic Regression (71%).
  • Checking balance flag and purpose of the loan appears to be the most important feature in the model

Conclusion
Thought the random forest has higher accuracy, i will choose the logistic regression model because of its interpretability and simplicity and especially in scenarios where understanding the model's decisions is essential

Recommendations and other fine tuning
Given the imbalanced class distribution, further exploration of techniques such as class weighting or sampling strategies may be beneficial to improve the model's performance, especially in predicting the "Bad" class.

ROC AUC CURVE¶

In [104]:
import sklearn.metrics as metrics
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

probs_1 = lr.predict_proba(X_test)
probs_2 = rfc.predict_proba(X_test)
preds_1 = probs_1[:, 1]
preds_2 = probs_1[:, 1]

fpr_1, tpr_1, threshold_1 = metrics.roc_curve(y_test, preds_1, pos_label='Good')
roc_auc_1 = metrics.auc(fpr_1, tpr_1)

fpr_2, tpr_2, threshold_2 = metrics.roc_curve(y_test, preds_2, pos_label='Good')
roc_auc_2 = metrics.auc(fpr_2, tpr_2)

# Increase figure size and linewidth
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic')
plt.plot(fpr_1, tpr_1, 'g', label='LR AUC = %0.2f' % roc_auc_1, linewidth=2)
plt.plot(fpr_2, tpr_2, 'b', label='RFC AUC = %0.2f' % roc_auc_2, linewidth=2)
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'r--', linewidth=2)
plt.xlim([0, 1])
plt.ylim([0, 1])
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.show()

An AUC (Area Under the Curve) value of 79% indicates that our model's performance in distinguishing between the good and bad classes is reasonably good
